after the Big Bang,
which is still

00:00:06.580 --> 00:00:10.910
roughly 13.7 billion years
ago, every point-- I shouldn't

00:00:10.910 --> 00:00:13.270
say every point--
every atom in space

00:00:13.270 --> 00:00:16.670
that was kind of at this
roughly 3,000 Kelvin temperature

00:00:16.670 --> 00:00:21.250
was emitting this
electromagnetic radiation.

00:00:21.250 --> 00:00:24.680
Since every point in space was,
there were points in space,

00:00:24.680 --> 00:00:26.560
or there was points
in the universe,

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:29.360
that that radiation is
only just now reaching us.

00:00:29.360 --> 00:00:33.172
It has been traveling
for 13.7 billion years.

00:00:33.172 --> 00:00:34.630
So when we look at
radiation that's

00:00:34.630 --> 00:00:38.230
been traveling for that long,
we can look at any direction

00:00:38.230 --> 00:00:40.980
and we'll see this
uniform radiation.

00:00:40.980 --> 00:00:44.620
And that radiation has been
red-shifted into the microwave

00:00:44.620 --> 00:00:46.080
range from the
higher frequencies

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:48.000
that it was actually emitted at.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:50.390
Now, a question that
might pop in your brain

00:00:50.390 --> 00:00:53.050
is, well, what happens if
we wait a billion years?

00:00:53.050 --> 00:00:54.990
Because if we wait
a billion years,

00:00:54.990 --> 00:00:59.480
if we have 1,000,380,000
years after the beginning

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:02.730
of the universe, this stuff
won't just be atoms anymore.

00:01:02.730 --> 00:01:08.480
It will have started to
condense into actual stars.

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:12.350
The universe at
every point in space

00:01:12.350 --> 00:01:14.700
will no longer be this uniform.

00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:18.040
We'll actually start having
condensation into stars.

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:23.880
So if we move forward a little
bit, the universe will expand.

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:26.230
Maybe I'll just draw a half
of it since it's expanded.

00:01:26.230 --> 00:01:27.900
It's obviously
expanded much more.

00:01:27.900 --> 00:01:30.670
But now all of a sudden,
we actually have stars.

00:01:30.670 --> 00:01:32.614
These are no longer
just uniform atoms

00:01:32.614 --> 00:01:33.780
spread through the universe.

00:01:33.780 --> 00:01:36.700
We actually have
condensation into stars.

00:01:36.700 --> 00:01:39.290
And so if you look at
what is being emitted

00:01:39.290 --> 00:01:43.360
from the points in space from
which we're only now getting

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:47.010
this cosmic background
radiation, if we wait

00:01:47.010 --> 00:01:49.000
a billion years,
the light that we

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.230
see from those points
in space will not

00:01:51.230 --> 00:01:53.560
look like this
uniform radiation.

00:01:53.560 --> 00:01:55.410
It'll start to look
a little bit more

00:01:55.410 --> 00:01:58.657
like the more mature
parts of the universe.

00:01:58.657 --> 00:02:00.490
We'll essentially be
looking at the universe

00:02:00.490 --> 00:02:03.530
a billion years after the Big
Bang, when stars have formed,

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:05.440
other structures have formed.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:07.410
So the question is
in a billion years,

00:02:07.410 --> 00:02:10.494
will this cosmic microwave
background radiation disappear.

00:02:10.494 --> 00:02:15.560
And I'm using billion just
to arbitrarily use a number.

00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:17.460
But will it
eventually disappear?

00:02:17.460 --> 00:02:21.250
And the answer to
that is yes and no.

00:02:21.250 --> 00:02:25.630
So to think about it, it is
true that this point in space

00:02:25.630 --> 00:02:27.050
will mature.

00:02:27.050 --> 00:02:29.180
It will mature in
a billion years.

00:02:29.180 --> 00:02:32.190
It will no longer
be this uniform--

00:02:32.190 --> 00:02:35.252
I guess this uniform haze
of hot hydrogen atoms.

00:02:35.252 --> 00:02:36.710
